00:21:29,404 --> 00:21:31,668
Straight trailing.

252
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:33,803
How the hell should I know?

253
00:21:43,985 --> 00:21:45,577
Oh, Christ.

254
00:22:13,381 --> 00:22:15,372
Oh, Mrs. Spangler.

255
00:22:15,584 --> 00:22:17,552
Religion's a little shaky.

256
00:22:17,752 --> 00:22:20,152
Oh, I forgot, I have to call
Sam O'Reilly about that.

257
00:22:20,355 --> 00:22:22,118
I better do it now.

258
00:22:26,394 --> 00:22:27,622
Damn it, Elmer.

259
00:22:27,829 --> 00:22:30,696
Someday I'm gonna take that cane
away from you.

260
00:22:44,646 --> 00:22:45,908
Hi.

261
00:22:46,114 --> 00:22:48,344
- Hi.
- How was the pie?

262
00:22:50,151 --> 00:22:51,880
Fine.

263
00:22:57,359 --> 00:22:58,656
Can I help you with something?

264
00:22:58,894 --> 00:23:02,022
Oh, no, thanks, just doing
a little college prep work.

265
00:23:02,864 --> 00:23:04,491
I can see.

266
00:23:07,402 --> 00:23:10,064
- Hey, what's your name?
- Why?

267
00:23:10,438 --> 00:23:11,564
What do you mean, why?

268
00:23:11,940 --> 00:23:13,840
I don't go out with strangers.

269
00:23:16,611 --> 00:23:18,374
Who said anything about going out?

270
00:23:18,780 --> 00:23:21,078
Besides, if you told me your name,
we wouldn't be strangers.

271
00:23:21,383 --> 00:23:23,317
I don't think so.

272
00:23:23,919 --> 00:23:26,888
Hey, how'd you like the flowers?

273
00:23:27,923 --> 00:23:29,914
Oh, so you're the one!

274
00:23:30,992 --> 00:23:33,324
Well, at least you're harmless.

275
00:23:33,528 --> 00:23:34,790
Harmless?

276
00:23:35,564 --> 00:23:36,963
What the hell's that mean?

277
00:23:37,165 --> 00:23:39,963
I mean, you could've been
some kind of maniac.

278
00:23:40,468 --> 00:23:42,527
Well, what makes you think
I'm so harmless?

279
00:23:42,938 --> 00:23:45,498
It's not supposed to be an insult.
What are you, some kind of a dolt?

280
00:23:45,707 --> 00:23:48,335
Oh, first I'm harmless, now...

281
00:23:52,914 --> 00:23:54,541
What the hell is this?

282
00:23:58,753 --> 00:24:02,416
Oh, I take it back,
you are definitely not harmless.

283
00:24:03,525 --> 00:24:05,493
Oh, isn't he a dream?

284
00:24:05,694 --> 00:24:07,719
Just looking at him
makes me feel dizzy.

285
00:24:07,929 --> 00:24:11,160
- What'll it be, girls?
- I'll have a grilled-cheese sandwich

286
00:24:11,366 --> 00:24:13,197
- and a cherry Coke.
- Me too.

287
00:24:13,735 --> 00:24:15,635
- So did you think about it?
- What?

288
00:24:15,837 --> 00:24:17,862
You know, Christmas Eve.

289
00:24:18,506 --> 00:24:20,098
- Oh, Gretchen.
- And?

290
00:24:20,308 --> 00:24:22,276
Oh, I don't know.

291
00:24:22,577 --> 00:24:25,068
Blind dates again. I hate new towns.

292
00:24:25,280 --> 00:24:26,838
Oh, come on, Caddie,
it'll be good for you.

293
00:24:27,048 --> 00:24:28,447
We'll have a ball, I promise.

294
00:24:28,750 --> 00:24:29,808
Just one night, right?

295
00:24:30,018 --> 00:24:31,542
He's shipping out
the day after Christmas.

296
00:24:31,753 --> 00:24:33,516
- You'll never see him again.
- You'll be there?

297
00:24:33,722 --> 00:24:34,916
- Every second.
- Do you promise?

298
00:24:35,123 --> 00:24:36,317
- Yes.
- Okay.

299
00:24:36,524 --> 00:24:37,582
Thanks, Caddie!

300
00:24:37,859 --> 00:24:39,417
He really... He's a dream!

301
00:24:39,628 --> 00:24:42,461
If he wasn't my cousin,
I'd go out with him.

302
00:24:42,731 --> 00:24:46,132
He looks just like Robert Walker.

303
00:24:46,334 --> 00:24:48,962
- I bet.
- Well, sort of.

304
00:24:49,170 --> 00:24:50,603
Who are you going with?

305
00:24:50,805 --> 00:24:53,330
I don't know. I was gonna go
with Bobby Michaels,

306
00:24:53,541 --> 00:24:56,203
but he says he's sworn off women
for the duration.

307
00:24:56,411 --> 00:24:58,038
Yeah, this war
is driving them all crazy.

308
00:24:58,246 --> 00:25:00,111
Why not go with one of the boys
from the theater?

309
00:25:00,315 --> 00:25:02,579
Too fresh. Last night,
Eddie Richards tried to drag me

310
00:25:02,784 --> 00:25:04,718
behind the popcorn machine.

311
00:25:04,919 --> 00:25:08,548
You're lucky you're in the booth.
Inside is hell.

312
00:25:09,090 --> 00:25:11,285
Hey, what about this guy?

313
00:25:12,560 --> 00:25:14,755
Henry? How do you know him?

314
00:25:15,030 --> 00:25:17,931
Henry and I sort of ran into each other
at the library.

315
00:25:18,133 --> 00:25:20,624
Henry Nash in the library?

316
00:25:20,835 --> 00:25:22,427
I didn't even think he knew
how to read.

317
00:25:22,637 --> 00:25:24,434
He's sort of cute, don't you think?

318
00:25:24,639 --> 00:25:25,731
Well...

319
00:25:26,608 --> 00:25:29,406
- Yeah, but I couldn't just ask him.
- Oh, come on.

320
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:32,171
- No, I couldn't ask him.
- Leave it to me. I'll do it. I'll do it.

321
00:25:32,380 --> 00:25:34,314
- Okay.
- Just watch this.

322
00:25:36,217 --> 00:25:37,684
Henry?

323
00:25:40,422 --> 00:25:43,550
I have to apologize, I'm afraid
I was awfully rude earlier.

324
00:25:43,758 --> 00:25:46,022
- Oh, that's all right.
- I didn't introduce myself.

325
00:25:46,227 --> 00:25:48,354
- My name's Caddie Winger.
- Henry Nash.

326
00:25:48,596 --> 00:25:51,121
Oh, it's a pleasure, Henry.

327
00:25:51,332 --> 00:25:53,061
Are you working this afternoon?

328
00:25:53,401 --> 00:25:54,732
Working?

329
00:25:54,936 --> 00:25:56,836
Yeah, you work here, don't you?

330
00:25:57,205 --> 00:25:59,901
Oh, you mean last night.
No, I was just helping out.

331
00:26:00,108 --> 00:26:01,200
Oh, that was nice of you.

332
00:26:01,409 --> 00:26:03,536
- I do what I can.
- Yeah.

333
00:26:03,745 --> 00:26:07,738
Henry, I don't suppose
you're free on Christmas Eve?

334
00:26:07,949 --> 00:26:10,042
- Christmas Eve?
- Yeah, you're probably spending it

335
00:26:10,251 --> 00:26:13,049
- with your family.
- Oh, with my family, right. No.

336
00:26:13,254 --> 00:26:14,721
Oh, no?

337
00:26:15,223 --> 00:26:20,388
Well, what I mean is, I would be,
but my mom, that's my mother,

338
00:26:20,595 --> 00:26:23,393
she's gonna be working
with the USO that night.

339
00:26:23,598 --> 00:26:25,429
And Dad...

340
00:26:25,667 --> 00:26:26,895
Dad's...

341
00:26:28,603 --> 00:26:30,730
- Dad's going fishing.
- Fishing?

342
00:26:30,939 --> 00:26:33,203
- Yeah.
- On Christmas Eve?

343
00:26:33,408 --> 00:26:34,534
Yeah.

344
00:26:34,876 --> 00:26:36,002
At night?

345
00:26:37,112 --> 00:26:39,046
Well, yeah, it's kind of a tradition.

346
00:26:39,247 --> 00:26:42,182
You know how other people
have turkey on Christmas?

347
00:26:42,383 --> 00:26:43,714
We have fish.

348
00:26:46,154 --> 00:26:50,750
Oh, that's great. Well, then,
you are free Christmas Eve?

349
00:26:51,192 --> 00:26:52,887
Definitely.

350
00:26:53,128 --> 00:26:54,959
- You wanna go out?
- Definitely.

351
00:26:55,163 --> 00:26:58,394
Really? Oh, that's great.
I believe you know Gretchen.

352
00:26:58,600 --> 00:27:00,158
- Hi, Henry.
- Hi.

353
00:27:00,568 --> 00:27:03,696
You two will have
such a wonderful time, I know it.

354
00:27:03,905 --> 00:27:07,204
It's perfect.
So anyway, we'll see you there.

355
00:27:09,611 --> 00:27:11,476
- Yeah, okay, see you there.
- Okay.

356
00:27:11,913 --> 00:27:13,380
Okay.

357
00:27:14,549 --> 00:27:17,950
Oh, Henry, we're gonna go
roller-skating. We'll meet at 7.

358
00:27:18,153 --> 00:27:21,611
- You do roller-skate, don't you?
- Sure.

359
00:27:27,462 --> 00:27:32,263
<i>Our men are the best-fed, best-paid,
best-uniformed soldiers in this war.</i>

360
00:27:38,673 --> 00:27:41,164
You look like a used-car salesman.

361
00:27:41,376 --> 00:27:43,606
Where are you going
dressed like that?

362
00:27:44,279 --> 00:27:45,678
I got a date.

363
00:27:45,980 --> 00:27:47,311
With who?

364
00:27:47,949 --> 00:27:49,416
A girl.

365
00:27:50,185 --> 00:27:52,449
What are you, Mr. District Attorney?

366
00:27:53,221 --> 00:27:55,553
A boy should stay home with his family
on Christmas Eve.

367
00:27:55,757 --> 00:27:58,157
I'll be home all day tomorrow, Ma.

368
00:27:59,027 --> 00:28:00,255
Merry Christmas.

369
00:28:01,196 --> 00:28:02,527
Hey.

370
00:28:02,730 --> 00:28:05,528
Oh, hi, Dad. Thanks for the flowers.

371
00:28:06,568 --> 00:28:09,969
Yeah, you look just like I did
the first time I wore that suit.

372
00:28:11,105 --> 00:28:13,767
- You don't think it's too big?
- You'll grow into it.

373
00:28:13,975 --> 00:28:15,169
By 8:00?

374
00:29:02,690 --> 00:29:04,419
There he is, I see him.

375
00:29:04,626 --> 00:29:06,389
Hey, Nash.

376
00:29:23,544 --> 00:29:25,068
You got your skates.

377
00:29:26,180 --> 00:29:29,638
Yeah, they wouldn't let me in
unless I put them on first.

378
00:29:29,951 --> 00:29:31,418
This is Michael.

379
00:29:31,619 --> 00:29:33,985
- Henry Nash.
- Glad to meet you.

380
00:29:34,956 --> 00:29:36,924
Michael just got his wings.

381
00:29:37,425 --> 00:29:39,120
- Congratulations.
- Thanks.

382
00:29:39,327 --> 00:29:40,692
What branch are you joining?

383
00:29:40,895 --> 00:29:43,420
- Marines.
- Tough group.

384
00:29:43,631 --> 00:29:46,031
I'll try not to drop anything
on you, huh?

385
00:29:49,437 --> 00:29:51,735
Sorry, everybody. Hi, Henry.

386
00:29:51,940 --> 00:29:53,373
These are for you.

387
00:29:53,574 --> 00:29:55,769
Oh, they're beautiful.

388
00:29:55,977 --> 00:29:57,410
Where'd you get them?

389
00:29:57,612 --> 00:29:59,944
I just kind of picked them up.

390
00:30:00,548 --> 00:30:02,948
Henry's very big on flowers.

391
00:30:03,151 --> 00:30:04,311
Aren't you?

392
00:30:04,886 --> 00:30:06,444
Yeah, sure.

393
00:30:08,456 --> 00:30:11,186
Well, shall we?

394
00:30:11,392 --> 00:30:12,950
All right.

395
00:30:17,598 --> 00:30:19,532
Something wrong?

396
00:30:19,834 --> 00:30:23,167
No. Go ahead.
I'm just gonna warm up.

397
00:30:23,905 --> 00:30:26,066
Okay.

398
00:30:33,948 --> 00:30:36,212
Hey, mister, leave me alone.

399
00:30:51,966 --> 00:30:53,456
Hey.

400
00:30:54,369 --> 00:30:56,337
Let go of my hand.

401
00:31:06,114 --> 00:31:07,376
Let go of my hand.

402
00:31:12,820 --> 00:31:14,219
Let go!

403
00:31:22,830 --> 00:31:24,627
That looked scary.

404
00:31:25,533 --> 00:31:27,967
Only if you don't know
what you're doing.

405
00:31:28,169 --> 00:31:29,727
That was great.

406
00:31:29,937 --> 00:31:31,404
Thanks very much.

407
00:31:31,606 --> 00:31:33,540
Does anyone feel like
taking a breather?

408
00:31:33,741 --> 00:31:35,072
I wouldn't mind.

409
00:31:35,276 --> 00:31:38,302
Well, Gretch, I guess
it's you and me, huh?

410
00:31:38,913 --> 00:31:40,904
You damn Marines.

411
00:31:41,115 --> 00:31:43,640
- You need a hand, huh?
- I do, yes.

412
00:31:54,262 --> 00:31:57,698
Hey, buddy. Hey, you're not allowed
on the floor without any skates.

413
00:31:57,899 --> 00:32:01,665
- No drinks either.
- Relax, I'm leaving.

414
00:32:04,705 --> 00:32:06,400
Here.

415
00:32:09,710 --> 00:32:11,302
Must've gotten a bad pair of skates.

416
00:32:11,512 --> 00:32:13,275
Yeah.

417
00:32:17,285 --> 00:32:18,877
So tell me about Michael.

418
00:32:20,021 --> 00:32:21,921
What do you wanna know
about Michael?

419
00:32:25,993 --> 00:32:27,392
Like...

420
00:32:28,930 --> 00:32:31,057
Like, is he my boyfriend
or something?

421
00:32:31,265 --> 00:32:32,664
Excuse me?

422
00:32:36,404 --> 00:32:38,872
So your dad's out fishing tonight,
isn't he?

423
00:32:39,073 --> 00:32:40,062
Fishing, right.

424
00:32:40,274 --> 00:32:41,502
No.

425
00:32:41,876 --> 00:32:43,309
No?

426
00:32:43,511 --> 00:32:46,810
- I sort of lied.
- You did? Why'd you do that?

427
00:32:53,421 --> 00:32:55,082
What does your dad do?

428
00:33:00,428 --> 00:33:02,157
He's a gravedigger.

429
00:33:03,364 --> 00:33:05,594
It's not all just digging holes,
like everybody thinks.

430
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:07,927
There's the grass and the flowers
to look after.

431
00:33:08,136 --> 00:33:09,831
Trees always need cutting back.

432
00:33:10,037 --> 00:33:13,370
Something about being near the ocean
makes everything grow faster.

433
00:33:13,574 --> 00:33:15,269
That's what he says.

434
00:33:16,777 --> 00:33:18,608
He keeps it real nice.

435
00:33:18,813 --> 00:33:20,542
It's a nice place.

436
00:33:21,816 --> 00:33:23,545
Why don't you
take me there sometime.

437
00:33:27,755 --> 00:33:29,518
She's a Gatsby girl.

438
00:33:29,724 --> 00:33:32,488
If you ask me, you're barking
up the wrong pair of gams.

439
00:33:32,693 --> 00:33:33,660
Who asked?

440
00:33:33,861 --> 00:33:36,557
- I'm just looking out for you!
- Right.

441
00:33:37,064 --> 00:33:38,998
All right, wise guy, listen to this:

442
00:33:39,200 --> 00:33:41,065
I heard the Nazis got this thing, right?

443
00:33:41,269 --> 00:33:43,829
It comes right out of the ground
and goes right for it.

444
00:33:44,038 --> 00:33:46,029
Blows the whole package right off.

445
00:33:46,240 --> 00:33:48,868
One second, you're John Wayne,
and the next, you're Minnie Mouse.

446
00:33:49,076 --> 00:33:50,976
- Nicky, there are other things.
- Yeah?

447
00:33:51,179 --> 00:33:52,146
- Yeah.
- Like what?

448
00:33:52,346 --> 00:33:53,313
Like, other things.

449
00:33:53,514 --> 00:33:56,745
Okay. I just hate to see you spend
the last few weeks of your manhood

450
00:33:56,951 --> 00:34:00,079
- chasing something you can't catch.
- Go away.

451
00:34:01,656 --> 00:34:03,647
Oh, I get it!

452
00:34:03,858 --> 00:34:05,325
You want a picture for your wallet.

453
00:34:05,526 --> 00:34:08,586
You want some girl who's gonna send
you flowers, poems and sweethearts...

454
00:34:08,796 --> 00:34:10,229
- Shut up!
- That's it, isn't it?

455
00:34:10,431 --> 00:34:12,729
- Yeah, well, what's wrong with that?
- Nothing.

456
00:34:13,201 --> 00:34:16,693
But I'll tell you something.
I ain't gonna be no sap to some skirt.

457
00:34:16,904 --> 00:34:19,964
Because when I finish killing Japs,
I ain't coming back here.

458
00:34:20,174 --> 00:34:22,665
I want nothing to do with this place.

459
00:34:34,722 --> 00:34:36,917
- Give me your hand.
- Thank you.

460
00:34:53,207 --> 00:34:54,834
- Here.
- What is this place?

461
00:34:55,042 --> 00:34:56,805
Danny's Tap Room.

462
00:34:57,345 --> 00:34:58,903
Or what's left of it.

463
00:35:00,181 --> 00:35:01,808
This is the stage.

464
00:35:02,350 --> 00:35:03,476
That...

465
00:35:03,684 --> 00:35:05,413
...used to be the bar.

466
00:35:06,053 --> 00:35:09,147
Over in the corner used to be
a couple of nickelodeon machines.

467
00:35:09,357 --> 00:35:11,587
They're gone now.
My dad used to sneak me in here.

468
00:35:12,560 --> 00:35:14,255
What do you do here?

469
00:35:14,895 --> 00:35:16,522
Whatever I want.

470
00:35:17,999 --> 00:35:19,466
What do you think?

471
00:35:21,836 --> 00:35:23,394
It's kind of spooky.

472
00:35:23,604 --> 00:35:25,333
- You wanna leave?
- No.

473
00:35:26,207 --> 00:35:28,402
Just feels like someone's listening.

474
00:35:33,914 --> 00:35:35,381
What is this?

475
00:35:39,086 --> 00:35:41,020
This is...

476
00:35:42,290 --> 00:35:43,621
...the best thing about this place.

477
00:35:43,824 --> 00:35:45,758
A piano.

478
00:35:46,394 --> 00:35:47,418
Does it work?

479
00:35:47,628 --> 00:35:49,152
- Plays up a storm.
- It couldn't.

480
00:35:49,363 --> 00:35:50,728
It could. It's magic.

481
00:35:50,931 --> 00:35:52,228
- Magic?
- Magic.

482
00:35:52,433 --> 00:35:53,593
- Do you play?
- A little.

483
00:35:53,801 --> 00:35:55,393
Play something.

484
00:36:45,519 --> 00:36:47,009
Not a key sticks.

485
00:36:47,521 --> 00:36:49,489
How'd you learn to play like that?

486
00:36:50,124 --> 00:36:51,523
Lessons.

487
00:36:53,394 --> 00:36:57,160
The day Eddie Richards tries to throw
Tommy Lester out at third base...

488
00:36:57,365 --> 00:36:58,832
...hits him in the head...

489
00:36:59,033 --> 00:37:00,625
...I'm doing this...

490
00:37:05,373 --> 00:37:07,500
...for Mr. Arthur, my teacher.

491
00:37:07,942 --> 00:37:10,035
Tommy gets a concussion...

492
00:37:10,678 --> 00:37:11,975
...and I miss it.

493
00:37:13,047 --> 00:37:15,572
And I've never forgiven my mother
for that.

494
00:37:18,352 --> 00:37:20,411
Wish I could play like that.

495
00:37:21,555 --> 00:37:22,647
Come here.

496
00:37:22,857 --> 00:37:24,017
Come here, I'll teach you.

497
00:37:24,358 --> 00:37:25,882
Come on, sit down.

498
00:37:29,964 --> 00:37:31,932
Okay, give me your hand.

499
00:37:32,767 --> 00:37:34,997
Okay, you do this.

500
00:37:42,276 --> 00:37:43,436
Repeat it.

501
00:37:54,422 --> 00:37:55,684
That's it?

502
00:37:55,890 --> 00:37:57,380
Well, you could try my part.

503
00:37:57,591 --> 00:37:59,183
What's your part?

504
00:38:36,130 --> 00:38:38,030
Think I'd better go.

505
00:38:44,872 --> 00:38:45,998
When do you leave?

506
00:38:47,408 --> 00:38:48,636
Next month.

507
00:39:13,797 --> 00:39:16,357
- Hi. Sorry, I forgot my key.
- Oh, it's all right.

